{"title":"Boosting Data Utilization for Multilingual Dense Retrieval","domain":"IR_REC","seeds":[{"problem":"Contrastive fine-tuning of multilingual dense retrievers is hindered by false negatives in hard-negative sets, since top-k retrieved candidates often include relevant but unjudged documents.","method":"Build a multilingual hard-negative candidate list by fusing representations from multiple retrievers (e.g., mE5, BGE) via a projection-and-concatenation fusion to score candidates, then use an LLM to judge each candidate’s relevance to the query and its positive (0/1/2 for irrelevant/partially/highly relevant) and keep only those judged irrelevant. This LLM-based filtering eliminates a substantial portion of false negatives (≈20% on average) and yields higher-quality negatives, outperforming strong TopK baselines (e.g., +2.5 nDCG@10 over TopK-PercPos on MIRACL)."},{"problem":"After filtering, many queries lack sufficient hard negatives and the remaining negatives lack diversity, especially for low-resource languages, limiting effective contrastive learning.","method":"Fine-tune a multilingual LLM (Llama3.1-70B-instruct) with translated Alpaca summarization instructions (Multilingual Instruction Fine-Tuning) to improve multilingual generation, then apply Positive-Driven Back-Forward Generation: summarize the positive document w.r.t. the query, generate a new query from the summary, and retrieve additional negatives with the retriever ensemble. Add top candidates until each query has a fixed N hard negatives, standardizing quantity and increasing diversity; ablations show both MIFT and PDBG contribute to gains."},{"problem":"In multilingual contrastive training, in-batch negatives from different languages are often too easy, and topic imbalance reduces semantic diversity, weakening supervision.","method":"Construct effective mini-batches by enforcing same-language samples (to make in-batch negatives harder) while diversifying topics using fastText-based topic labels derived from DBpedia Ontology and Yahoo Answers. Uniformly sample across language/topic to represent low-resource and underrepresented categories, and integrate language/topic-aware sampling weights into the contrastive loss. Ablations confirm both same-language batching and topic balancing improve retrieval performance."}]}
